key_concepts.explanation:
Real-world decisions are rarely simple. You often combine multiple conditions using && (AND), || (OR), and ! (NOT).

Real-world analogy: Booking a hotel room. You need: valid dates AND (credit card OR loyalty points) AND room available AND NOT on the blocked list. Multiple conditions, multiple operators, but one final YES or NO.

Best practices for complex conditions:
  1. Use parentheses to make grouping explicit
  2. Break long conditions across lines for readability
  3. Extract conditions into well-named boolean variables
  4. Test edge cases where conditions are barely true/false

Named booleans pattern:
  boolean isAdult = age >= 18;
  boolean hasID = id != null;
  boolean canEnter = isAdult && hasID;
  if (canEnter) { ... }

This is MUCH clearer than: if (age >= 18 && id != null) { ... }

